<h2>Monitoring and Adjustment</h2>

<p>Once on thyroid replacement, monitoring is ongoing:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Month 6:</strong> Repeat TSH, Free T3, Free T4. Assess symptom improvement. Adjust dose if needed (typical titration: 12.5-25 mcg increments every 6 weeks).</li>
  <li><strong>Month 12:</strong> Repeat full panel. If stable and asymptomatic, extend to annual monitoring.</li>
  <li><strong>Annually:</strong> TSH, Free T3, Free T4, Anti-TPO. Ongoing assessment prevents over- or under-replacement.</li>
</ul>

<p>Symptoms typically improve within 4-8 weeks of starting appropriate replacement. If you're on levothyroxine but still fatigued, depressed, or gaining weight after 3 months at stable dose, something is wrong — poor absorption, inadequate dose, conversion issues, or concurrent problems (iron deficiency, B12 deficiency, sleep apnea). Further investigation is needed.</p>

