  </div>
  <ul class="faq-list">
    <li class="faq-item">
      <details>
        <summary>Is TSH alone enough to diagnose thyroid disease?</summary>
        <div class="faq-ans">No. TSH is a screening marker, not a diagnostic test. Elevated TSH suggests hypothyroidism, but doesn't tell you what's causing it or whether you need treatment. Normal TSH doesn't rule out thyroid disease — you can have subclinical hypothyroidism (TSH 2.5-4.5 with symptoms), autoimmune thyroid disease (high Anti-TPO), or poor T4-to-T3 conversion (normal TSH but low Free T3). A full panel including Free T3, Free T4, and thyroid antibodies is necessary for diagnosis and treatment decisions.</div>
      </details>
    </li>
    <li class="faq-item">
      <details>
        <summary>What is subclinical hypothyroidism and why does it matter?</summary>
        <div class="faq-ans">Subclinical hypothyroidism occurs when TSH is elevated (typically 2.5-4.5 mIU/L) but Free T4 is still normal. You may have symptoms — fatigue, weight gain, cold intolerance, hair loss, depression — despite a 'normal' Free T4. Many Indian doctors ignore subclinical hypothyroidism and tell patients to monitor. But studies show treating TSH above 2.5 when symptomatic improves outcomes. The disease is there; the TSH-only approach just misses it.</div>
      </details>
    </li>
    <li class="faq-item">
      <details>
        <summary>What does Anti-TPO tell me about thyroid disease?</summary>
        <div class="faq-ans">Anti-TPO (thyroid peroxidase antibody) detects autoimmune thyroid disease — Hashimoto's thyroiditis. High Anti-TPO can appear YEARS before TSH rises, meaning you have early-stage autoimmune disease while your TSH is still 'normal.' This is critical: if Anti-TPO is positive, you need aggressive monitoring, selenium/iodine supplementation, and eventual thyroid hormone replacement as disease progresses. Catching high Anti-TPO early prevents years of undiagnosed hypothyroidism.</div>
      </details>
    </li>
    <li class="faq-item">
      <details>
        <summary>What is Reverse T3 and why might it be high?</summary>
        <div class="faq-ans">Reverse T3 (rT3) is an inactive form of thyroid hormone. Your body produces it as a buffer during stress, poor nutrition, or illness. High rT3 with normal TSH and Free T4 means your thyroid hormones are being shunted into an inactive form — you feel hypothyroid (fatigue, cold, weight gain) despite 'normal' lab values. This happens with chronic stress, inadequate sleep, poor gut health, or nutrient deficiencies. Treating rT3 requires addressing the root cause: sleep, stress management, gut health, iron, selenium.</div>
      </details>
    </li>
    <li class="faq-item">
      <details>
        <summary>Can you have normal TSH but low Free T3 (poor conversion)?</summary>
        <div class="faq-ans">Yes, and this is common. Your thyroid produces mostly T4 (inactive); your body converts T4 to T3 (active) in the liver, gut, and tissues. Poor conversion — high T4, low T3, normal TSH — causes hypothyroid symptoms (fatigue, brain fog, cold intolerance) despite appearing 'normal' on standard testing. This happens with selenium/iodine deficiency, gut dysbiosis, poor liver health, or chronic stress. The fix: supplement selenium (200 mcg daily), fix gut health, add T3 to levothyroxine if needed.</div>
      </details>
    </li>
    <li class="faq-item">
      <details>
        <summary>Why do women have higher thyroid disease rates than men?</summary>
        <div class="faq-ans">Autoimmune thyroid disease is 5-10x more common in women, likely due to immune system differences and hormonal factors. Pregnancy and postpartum are critical periods — thyroid antibodies spike, TSH fluctuates, and hypothyroidism often emerges postpartum. Women also experience more severe symptoms at the same TSH level as men. Additionally, women are more likely to be dismissed with 'it's just stress' or 'it's depression' when the real cause is thyroid disease. In India, where 42 million people are affected, the majority are women, and the majority are undiagnosed.</div>
      </details>
    </li>
    <li class="faq-item">
      <details>
        <summary>What's the difference between levothyroxine and natural desiccated thyroid (NDT)?</summary>
        <div class="faq-ans">Levothyroxine (synthetic T4) is the standard treatment and works well for most people. Your body converts T4 to active T3 as needed. NDT (natural desiccated thyroid from pig thyroid glands) contains both T4 and T3 in fixed ratios. Some people feel better on NDT because they get T3 immediately rather than relying on conversion. However, NDT dosing is less precise and quality varies. Most physicians start levothyroxine; if you have persistent symptoms despite normal TSH and adequate T4, your physician may trial NDT or add T3. arq. physicians tailor treatment to your response.</div>
      </details>
    </li>
    <li class="faq-item">
      <details>
        <summary>Why does thyroid disease get misdiagnosed as depression or PCOS?</summary>
        <div class="faq-ans">Hypothyroidism causes depression, fatigue, brain fog, and mood changes that look identical to depression. PCOS (polycystic ovary syndrome) causes irregular periods, weight gain, and hair loss — also identical to thyroid disease. Because Indian doctors often only test TSH, and TSH can be 'normal' in subclinical disease, they miss thyroid as the cause. Result: a woman gets antidepressants or PCOS management when she actually needs thyroid treatment. The fix: full thyroid panel (TSH, Free T3, Free T4, Anti-TPO) before diagnosing depression or assuming PCOS. Treating the real cause changes everything.</div>
      </details>
    </li>
